1
00:02:56,750 --> 00:02:58,126
The usurper.

2
00:03:00,003 --> 00:03:02,380
Caro? He's here.

3
00:03:23,109 --> 00:03:25,153
Professor Perlman.
Welcome, welcome.

4
00:03:25,237 --> 00:03:27,322
Thank you so much for having me.
Oh, my goodness.

5
00:03:27,405 --> 00:03:28,865
You're bigger than your picture.

6
00:03:28,949 --> 00:03:30,510
Well, I couldn't get
all of me in the photo.

7
00:03:30,534 --> 00:03:32,285
That's the problem.

8
00:03:32,828 --> 00:03:34,287
He seems very confident.

9
00:03:35,372 --> 00:03:36,748
Mrs. Perlman.
Annella.

10
00:03:36,832 --> 00:03:38,208
Oliver. Very nice to meet you.

11
00:03:38,291 --> 00:03:39,769
Thank you for having me in your home.
Welcome.

12
00:03:39,793 --> 00:03:41,044
Where's Elio?

13
00:03:41,419 --> 00:03:42,587
I'll go down.

14
00:03:42,671 --> 00:03:43,922
Elio?

15
00:03:44,005 --> 00:03:47,217
You must be exhausted.
What gave me away?

16
00:03:58,854 --> 00:03:59,855
Hey.

17
00:03:59,980 --> 00:04:02,440
Darling, come help Oliver
take his things up to his room.

18
00:04:02,524 --> 00:04:03,942
He's already here?
Yes!

19
00:04:04,734 --> 00:04:07,153
Every single one of these will.

20
00:04:07,279 --> 00:04:09,155
Elio, Oliver. Oliver, Elio.

21
00:04:09,239 --> 00:04:10,991
How you doing?
Nice to meet you. Elio.

22
00:04:11,074 --> 00:04:12,784
You must be exhausted.

23
00:04:12,868 --> 00:04:14,995
A little bit.
Come, come, come.

24
00:04:15,078 --> 00:04:16,830
May I bring your things up to your room?

25
00:04:16,913 --> 00:04:18,999
Sure. Yeah.
My room?

26
00:04:21,293 --> 00:04:23,044
Follow him.

27
00:04:23,128 --> 00:04:25,297
You're very welcome here.
Si.

28
00:04:25,422 --> 00:04:27,340
Our home is your home.

29
00:04:33,555 --> 00:04:34,890
You're leaving?

30
00:04:34,973 --> 00:04:38,018
Hello.
Hi.

31
00:04:38,894 --> 00:04:39,978
Nice to meet you.

32
00:05:06,254 --> 00:05:08,632
My room is now your room.

33
00:05:08,715 --> 00:05:10,550
I'll be next door.

34
00:05:14,137 --> 00:05:16,848
We have to share the bathroom.

35
00:05:17,515 --> 00:05:19,059
It's my only way out.

36
00:06:09,943 --> 00:06:12,112
We're being called for dinner.

37
00:06:53,903 --> 00:06:55,697
Sorry.

38
00:06:57,198 --> 00:06:58,366
Yeah.

39
00:06:58,450 --> 00:07:00,243
We're being called for dinner.

40
00:07:00,660 --> 00:07:03,788
Yeah, I'm probably gonna pass.

41
00:07:03,872 --> 00:07:06,541
Will you make an excuse for me
to your mom, though?

42
00:07:08,543 --> 00:07:10,336
Thanks, man.

43
00:07:12,672 --> 00:07:14,674
So, this is your old room, huh?

44
00:07:17,302 --> 00:07:18,428
Thanks.

45
00:07:20,472 --> 00:07:21,931
Later.

46
00:08:09,687 --> 00:08:11,397
I'll take care of the tart.

47
00:08:15,610 --> 00:08:16,945
Look at this.

48
00:08:17,028 --> 00:08:18,363
Good morning, Professor.

49
00:08:18,446 --> 00:08:19,906
Good morning.
Back from the dead.

50
00:08:19,989 --> 00:08:21,991
Was I out that long?
It seemed like it, huh?

51
00:08:22,075 --> 00:08:24,452
How are you?
I... Well, rested now.

52
00:08:24,536 --> 00:08:25,995
Thank you.
I'm glad.

53
00:08:26,079 --> 00:08:27,372
Would you like some espresso?

54
00:08:27,455 --> 00:08:29,457
I would love some. Thank you very much.

55
00:08:29,541 --> 00:08:31,876
This looks amazing.
I didn't take your seat, did I?

56
00:08:31,960 --> 00:08:34,671
No, no, no. It's okay. Please.

57
00:08:34,754 --> 00:08:36,714
Did you...
Did you recover from your trip?

58
00:08:36,798 --> 00:08:38,174
I did. Yeah, big time.

59
00:08:38,258 --> 00:08:39,968
Thank you.
Good.

60
00:08:40,051 --> 00:08:41,636
I could show you around.

61
00:08:41,719 --> 00:08:43,346
That'd be great. Thank you.

62
00:08:43,429 --> 00:08:45,348
Is there a... Is there a bank in town?

63
00:08:45,431 --> 00:08:47,725
I'd love to start
an account while I'm here.

64
00:08:48,893 --> 00:08:50,395
Let me do it.

65
00:08:50,478 --> 00:08:51,688
Sorry.

66
00:08:52,188 --> 00:08:55,233
It happens to the best of us.
Yeah, well...

67
00:08:55,316 --> 00:08:58,236
None of our residents has ever
had a local bank account.

68
00:08:58,319 --> 00:08:59,779
Really?

69
00:08:59,863 --> 00:09:01,656
Should I take him to Montodine?

70
00:09:01,739 --> 00:09:03,950
I think they're closed
for summer vacation.

71
00:09:04,033 --> 00:09:06,411
You try Crema.

72
00:09:06,494 --> 00:09:07,787
Crema?

73
00:09:07,912 --> 00:09:09,372
Thank you.

74
00:09:09,497 --> 00:09:11,040
Is this your orchard?

75
00:09:11,124 --> 00:09:12,542
These are Annella's trees.

76
00:09:13,418 --> 00:09:16,504
Peaches, cherries, apricots...

77
00:09:17,964 --> 00:09:19,340
Pomegranate.

78
00:09:25,096 --> 00:09:26,890
Have another egg.

79
00:09:26,973 --> 00:09:28,391
Oh, stupid.

80
00:09:28,474 --> 00:09:30,268
No, no, no. I know myself too well.

81
00:09:30,351 --> 00:09:31,996
If I have a second,
I'm just gonna have a third,

82
00:09:32,020 --> 00:09:34,940
and then a fourth, and then you're just
gonna have to roll me out of here.

83
00:09:36,024 --> 00:09:37,942
Delicious.
Darling?

84
00:09:38,026 --> 00:09:39,444
Thank you.

85
00:09:40,028 --> 00:09:41,946
Shall I give him Anchise's bike?

86
00:10:18,483 --> 00:10:21,069
So, what does one do around here?

87
00:10:21,152 --> 00:10:23,780
Wait for the summer to end.

88
00:10:23,863 --> 00:10:25,281
Yeah?

89
00:10:25,365 --> 00:10:26,574
What do you do in the winter?

90
00:10:26,658 --> 00:10:29,869
Wait for summer to come?
Well, we only come here for Christmas

91
00:10:29,953 --> 00:10:31,537
and some other vacations.

92
00:10:31,621 --> 00:10:33,057
Christmas? I thought you...
And Easter as well.

93
00:10:33,081 --> 00:10:34,642
Thought you were Jewish.
Well, we are Jewish,

94
00:10:34,666 --> 00:10:36,918
but also American, Italian, French.

95
00:10:37,001 --> 00:10:39,254
Somewhat atypical combination.

96
00:10:40,755 --> 00:10:42,215
Besides my family, you're probably

97
00:10:42,298 --> 00:10:44,217
the only other Jew
to set foot in this town.

98
00:10:45,426 --> 00:10:47,178
I'm from a small town in New England.

99
00:10:47,262 --> 00:10:48,982
I know what it's like
to be the odd Jew out.

100
00:10:50,390 --> 00:10:52,350
So, what do you do around here?

101
00:10:53,601 --> 00:10:55,687
Just read books.

102
00:10:55,770 --> 00:10:58,856
Transcribe music. Swim at the river.

103
00:10:58,940 --> 00:11:00,608
Yeah?
Go out at night.

104
00:11:00,692 --> 00:11:02,902
I don't know.
That sounds fun.

105
00:11:06,656 --> 00:11:08,700
All right, buddy, thanks for the help.

106
00:11:17,792 --> 00:11:19,460
Sorry. Sorry about that.

107
00:11:19,544 --> 00:11:21,004
It's all right.

108
00:11:21,087 --> 00:11:23,089
All right, later.

109
00:11:33,308 --> 00:11:34,726
What do you have there?

110
00:11:34,809 --> 00:11:36,728
That should all be...

111
00:11:40,356 --> 00:11:41,649
What is this?

112
00:11:41,733 --> 00:11:46,237
These are the continuation
of these archaeology department...

113
00:11:46,738 --> 00:11:47,905
These are archaeology?

114
00:11:47,989 --> 00:11:49,758
Yeah, those are archaeology.
The rest of these should be history.

115
00:11:49,782 --> 00:11:50,867
Okay.

116
00:11:50,950 --> 00:11:53,328
More apricot juice?
Yeah.

117
00:11:54,162 --> 00:11:55,830
Here, tesoro.
Thank you.

118
00:11:55,913 --> 00:11:57,290
Help yourself, darling.

119
00:11:57,373 --> 00:11:58,666
Thanks.

120
00:12:06,799 --> 00:12:08,259
Help yourself to some more.

121
00:12:09,344 --> 00:12:13,431
The word "apricot"
comes from the Arabic.

122
00:12:13,514 --> 00:12:17,101
It's like the words "algebra,"
"alchemy," "alcohol."

123
00:12:17,185 --> 00:12:18,770
It derives from an Arabic noun

124
00:12:18,853 --> 00:12:20,772
combined with the Arabic article "al"
before it.

125
00:12:20,855 --> 00:12:24,776
The origin of our Italian albicocca

126
00:12:24,859 --> 00:12:26,486
is al-barquq.

127
00:12:26,569 --> 00:12:28,988
It's amazing that today in Israel
and many Arab countries,

128
00:12:29,072 --> 00:12:32,742
the fruit's referred to
by a totally different name, mismish.

129
00:12:33,326 --> 00:12:35,703
I may have to disagree
with you there, Professor.

130
00:12:37,205 --> 00:12:39,499
I'm gonna talk etymology,
so just bear with me a second.

131
00:12:40,416 --> 00:12:42,019
You're right in the case
that most Latin words

132
00:12:42,043 --> 00:12:44,295
do find their origins in Greek words.

133
00:12:44,379 --> 00:12:45,739
However, in the case of "apricot,"

134
00:12:45,797 --> 00:12:47,649
it's a little bit more
of a complicated journey.

135
00:12:47,673 --> 00:12:49,133
How so?

136
00:12:49,467 --> 00:12:52,178
Well, here, the Greek actually
takes over from the Latin.

137
00:12:52,261 --> 00:12:55,223
Latin word being
praecoquum or precoquere.

138
00:12:55,306 --> 00:12:57,117
So it's, "precook" or "pre-ripen,"
as you know.

139
00:12:57,141 --> 00:12:58,810
To be precocious or premature.

140
00:12:59,560 --> 00:13:03,731
And the Byzantines, to go on,
then borrowed praecox,

141
00:13:03,815 --> 00:13:07,151
which became prekokkia,
which then became berikokki,

142
00:13:07,235 --> 00:13:09,070
which is how the Arabs got al-barquq.

143
00:13:20,039 --> 00:13:21,749
That's courtesy of Philology 101.

144
00:13:22,792 --> 00:13:24,419
Flying colors.

145
00:13:28,172 --> 00:13:29,715
He does this every year.

146
00:13:45,565 --> 00:13:48,025
It's about drink time. Let's go here.

147
00:13:49,193 --> 00:13:51,195
Ciao, Romano.
Ciao, Oliver.

148
00:13:51,279 --> 00:13:53,865
How are you?
All good.

149
00:13:59,120 --> 00:14:00,663
Ciao, boys!

150
00:14:00,746 --> 00:14:02,582
All good?

151
00:14:02,665 --> 00:14:04,333
All good!

152
00:14:04,417 --> 00:14:05,918
Let's see. What have we got?

153
00:14:06,002 --> 00:14:08,838
Can you start please?
Of course!

154
00:14:29,525 --> 00:14:30,776
Good morning, gentlemen.

155
00:14:35,823 --> 00:14:37,825
How do you know about this place?

156
00:14:39,494 --> 00:14:40,995
Okay.

157
00:14:41,245 --> 00:14:42,830
Go, Chiara!

158
00:14:49,629 --> 00:14:51,631
No, no, no, no, no!

159
00:14:51,714 --> 00:14:54,175
He's better than the guy
who came last year.

160
00:14:54,258 --> 00:14:55,635
Remember?

161
00:14:56,135 --> 00:14:57,553
Get in there!

162
00:14:57,637 --> 00:15:00,515
Much better!
See how cute he is.

163
00:15:12,235 --> 00:15:13,736
Elio, water!

164
00:15:15,321 --> 00:15:16,531
Perfect timing.

165
00:15:20,159 --> 00:15:21,639
What's the matter? Are you all right?

166
00:15:22,370 --> 00:15:24,497
What, pinch a nerve?
I'm okay.

167
00:15:24,622 --> 00:15:26,499
Here. Hold this.

168
00:15:26,582 --> 00:15:28,584
Trust me. I'm about to be a doctor.

169
00:15:28,668 --> 00:15:30,428
Hey, hey, come here.
See? That's the problem.

170
00:15:30,503 --> 00:15:31,754
You're too stressed.

171
00:15:31,837 --> 00:15:34,298
You just gotta relax a little bit.
I am relaxing.

172
00:15:34,382 --> 00:15:36,133
Marzia, come here for a minute.

173
00:15:36,217 --> 00:15:38,594
Back me up here.

174
00:15:39,095 --> 00:15:40,513
Feel that. Right there?
Oliver.

175
00:15:40,596 --> 00:15:41,847
It's too tight, right?
Yeah.

176
00:15:41,931 --> 00:15:43,140
He needs to relax.
Oliver!

177
00:15:43,224 --> 00:15:44,475
Later.

178
00:15:44,559 --> 00:15:46,018
You should relax more.

179
00:15:48,020 --> 00:15:49,438
Okay, guys, ready?

180
00:15:56,862 --> 00:15:58,739
Okay, our ball, our ball, our ball.

181
00:15:58,823 --> 00:16:01,117
Twelve serving 11.

182
00:16:01,200 --> 00:16:02,994
Mine, mine, mine, mine.

183
00:16:03,077 --> 00:16:05,371
Go, go, go. Yeah, good.
It's yours, it's yours.

184
00:16:06,706 --> 00:16:10,334
Sweetheart, Auntie Marcella and
the others are coming over for dinner.

185
00:16:11,127 --> 00:16:13,838
Is Oliver staying with us or going out?

186
00:16:13,921 --> 00:16:15,256
Don't know.

187
00:16:16,173 --> 00:16:17,633
What a movie star!

188
00:16:17,883 --> 00:16:20,428
Yes, those Americans...

189
00:16:43,743 --> 00:16:45,661
Sparkling wine!

190
00:16:46,621 --> 00:16:47,997
He's late.

191
00:16:49,373 --> 00:16:50,666
Don't you think...

192
00:16:51,626 --> 00:16:54,670
Don't you think he's impolite
when he says, "Later"?

193
00:16:55,838 --> 00:16:57,465
Arrogant.

194
00:16:57,548 --> 00:16:59,884
I don't think he's arrogant.

195
00:16:59,967 --> 00:17:01,135
Just watch.

196
00:17:01,218 --> 00:17:03,554
This is how he'll say good-bye
to us when the time comes.

197
00:17:03,638 --> 00:17:05,848
With his... "Later."

198
00:17:07,141 --> 00:17:09,852
Meanwhile, we'll have to put up with him
for six long weeks.

199
00:17:09,935 --> 00:17:12,063
Won't we, darling?

200
00:17:13,022 --> 00:17:14,482
I think he's shy.

201
00:17:14,774 --> 00:17:16,233
You'll grow to like him.

202
00:17:16,317 --> 00:17:17,397
What if I grow to hate him?

203
00:17:17,443 --> 00:17:18,611
Oh, no, sweetheart.

204
00:17:20,821 --> 00:17:23,407
Take his plates away.
Very well, madam.

205
00:17:26,869 --> 00:17:28,579
Darling?

206
00:17:48,057 --> 00:17:50,601
Elio, play something.

207
00:17:50,685 --> 00:17:52,395
I don't want to.

208
00:17:53,229 --> 00:17:54,438
Why not?

209
00:17:54,522 --> 00:17:55,981
Because I don't want to.

210
00:17:56,065 --> 00:17:58,401
Why don't you go
to Moscazzano with others?

211
00:17:58,484 --> 00:18:00,194
Because I don't want to.

212
00:18:00,695 --> 00:18:02,405
You're spoiling everyone's fun.

213
00:18:10,913 --> 00:18:12,540
Play well, darling.

214
00:19:45,674 --> 00:19:47,551
Hey.
Hey.

215
00:19:47,635 --> 00:19:48,928
What are you doing?

216
00:19:49,011 --> 00:19:50,221
Reading.

217
00:19:52,056 --> 00:19:54,296
How come you're not with everyone else
down by the river?

218
00:19:55,434 --> 00:19:58,229
I have an allergy. It's...
Yeah, me too.

219
00:19:58,312 --> 00:20:00,481
Maybe we have the same one.

220
00:20:03,526 --> 00:20:05,027
Why don't you and I go swimming?

221
00:20:05,110 --> 00:20:07,029
Right now?
Yeah.

222
00:20:07,112 --> 00:20:09,281
Come on. Let's go.

223
00:20:09,406 --> 00:20:11,659
Do we have to go right now?

224
00:20:13,285 --> 00:20:14,662
I'll go get changed.
Okay.

225
00:20:14,745 --> 00:20:16,205
Meet you downstairs.

226
00:20:35,182 --> 00:20:36,392
See you downstairs.

227
00:21:11,218 --> 00:21:13,804
Elio, what are you doing?

228
00:21:13,888 --> 00:21:15,472
Reading my music.

229
00:21:15,556 --> 00:21:17,933
No, you're not.

230
00:21:18,017 --> 00:21:20,185
Thinking, then.
Yeah?

231
00:21:23,355 --> 00:21:24,690
About what?

232
00:21:27,318 --> 00:21:28,736
It's private.

233
00:21:29,320 --> 00:21:30,571
You're not gonna tell me?

234
00:21:30,654 --> 00:21:32,406
I'm not gonna tell you.

235
00:21:32,489 --> 00:21:34,408
He's not gonna tell me
what he's thinking about.

236
00:21:34,491 --> 00:21:35,576
Elio.

237
00:21:35,659 --> 00:21:37,328
I guess I'll go hang out with your mom.

238
00:21:38,495 --> 00:21:40,497
More apricot juice, please.

239
00:21:41,832 --> 00:21:43,584
That's a good boy.

240
00:21:43,667 --> 00:21:45,210
Thank God you're helping me.

241
00:22:07,399 --> 00:22:09,318
Sounds nice.

242
00:22:09,985 --> 00:22:11,612
Thought you didn't like it.

243
00:22:17,534 --> 00:22:18,994
Play it again, will you?

244
00:22:28,671 --> 00:22:30,339
Follow me.

245
00:23:02,621 --> 00:23:04,665
That sounds different.
Did you change it?

246
00:23:04,748 --> 00:23:07,418
Well, I changed it a little bit.
Why?

247
00:23:07,501 --> 00:23:09,586
I just played it the way Liszt
would have played it

248
00:23:09,670 --> 00:23:11,964
if he'd altered Bach's version.

249
00:23:12,047 --> 00:23:13,924
Play that again.

250
00:23:14,049 --> 00:23:16,051
Play what again?
The thing you played outside.

251
00:23:16,135 --> 00:23:18,429
You want me to play
the thing I played outside?

252
00:23:18,512 --> 00:23:21,473
Please.
Of course.

253
00:23:45,039 --> 00:23:46,582
I can't believe you changed it again.

254
00:23:46,665 --> 00:23:49,209
I changed it a little bit.
Yeah. Why?

255
00:23:49,293 --> 00:23:51,670
I just played it the way
Busoni would've played it

256
00:23:51,754 --> 00:23:53,255
if he'd altered Liszt's version.

257
00:23:53,338 --> 00:23:55,316
And what is wrong with Bach
the way Bach would've played...

258
00:23:55,340 --> 00:23:56,884
Bach never wrote it for the guitar.

259
00:23:56,967 --> 00:23:58,302
In fact, we're not even sure.

260
00:23:58,385 --> 00:24:00,262
Bach wrote it at all.
Forget I asked.

261
00:24:30,626 --> 00:24:32,419
It's young Bach.

262
00:24:32,503 --> 00:24:34,379
He dedicated it to his brother.

263
00:25:08,038 --> 00:25:09,623
Hey, Professor.

264
00:25:09,748 --> 00:25:10,874
Hello.

265
00:25:10,958 --> 00:25:13,085
Here, please.

266
00:25:13,168 --> 00:25:14,753
I need help.

267
00:25:16,755 --> 00:25:18,215
Just be honest.

268
00:25:18,340 --> 00:25:19,508
How bad is it?

269
00:25:19,633 --> 00:25:23,220
I think your insights here
are persuasive, but...

270
00:25:26,765 --> 00:25:28,725
Have you been to the river?

271
00:25:43,073 --> 00:25:44,408
Mafalda!

272
00:25:44,992 --> 00:25:46,326
Isn't she beautiful?

273
00:26:05,971 --> 00:26:07,222
Elio.

274
00:26:08,432 --> 00:26:09,933
You sleeping?

275
00:26:11,393 --> 00:26:12,728
I was.

276
00:26:12,811 --> 00:26:15,480
Listen to this drivel.
Tell me what you think.

277
00:26:16,356 --> 00:26:18,775
Wait.
What?

278
00:26:18,859 --> 00:26:20,569
Can't hear you.

279
00:26:29,661 --> 00:26:31,496
"For the early Greeks,

280
00:26:31,580 --> 00:26:33,266
"Heidegger contends,
this underlying hiddenness

281
00:26:33,290 --> 00:26:35,083
"is constitutive of the way beings are,

282
00:26:35,167 --> 00:26:36,561
"not only in relation to themselves

283
00:26:36,585 --> 00:26:39,213
"but also in relation
to other entities generally.

284
00:26:39,296 --> 00:26:41,065
"In other words,
they do not construe hiddenness

285
00:26:41,089 --> 00:26:44,593
"merely or primarily in terms of
entities' relations to human beings."

286
00:26:45,969 --> 00:26:48,013
Does that make any sense to you?

287
00:26:48,096 --> 00:26:50,474
Doesn't make any sense to me.

288
00:26:50,557 --> 00:26:52,637
I don't think it makes
any sense to your dad, either.

289
00:26:53,852 --> 00:26:55,562
Maybe it did when you wrote it.

290
00:27:00,525 --> 00:27:03,362
That might be the kindest thing
anybody has said to me in months.

291
00:27:04,071 --> 00:27:06,073
"Kind"?

292
00:27:06,156 --> 00:27:08,158
Yep. Kind.

293
00:27:33,809 --> 00:27:37,020
Hey, Elio.
Hey.

294
00:27:37,104 --> 00:27:38,480
Hey!

295
00:27:41,316 --> 00:27:42,484
Come here.

296
00:27:44,820 --> 00:27:46,238
What's going on?

297
00:27:46,321 --> 00:27:48,115
Is he trying to get it on with her?

298
00:27:48,240 --> 00:27:50,367
Elio, he already succeeded?

299
00:27:52,286 --> 00:27:53,704
What do I know?

300
00:27:53,787 --> 00:27:55,455
I'd love to be in his shoes.

301
00:27:55,539 --> 00:27:57,457
Who wouldn't love to be in her shoes?

302
00:27:59,918 --> 00:28:02,170
She wants him, no matter what!

303
00:28:46,423 --> 00:28:47,591
Coming?

304
00:28:49,926 --> 00:28:51,261
I'll come later.

305
00:30:06,670 --> 00:30:09,548
Are you with me because
you're mad at Chiara?

306
00:30:09,631 --> 00:30:11,299
Why would I be mad at Chiara?

307
00:30:12,509 --> 00:30:14,010
Because of him.

308
00:30:14,094 --> 00:30:15,554
Because of who?

309
00:30:16,721 --> 00:30:17,973
Of Oliver.

310
00:30:29,484 --> 00:30:30,861
Turn around.

311
00:30:45,500 --> 00:30:47,335
Meet me here tomorrow night?

312
00:30:54,217 --> 00:30:56,511
Wait for me!

313
00:30:56,595 --> 00:30:58,138
Come on.

314
00:31:11,568 --> 00:31:13,570
We almost had sex last night...

315
00:31:13,653 --> 00:31:16,031
Marzia and me.

316
00:31:17,824 --> 00:31:19,534
Well, why didn't you?

317
00:31:20,327 --> 00:31:21,828
I don't know.

318
00:31:22,954 --> 00:31:25,665
Well, you know, it's better
to have tried and failed, right?

319
00:31:25,749 --> 00:31:29,544
All I had to do was find the courage
to reach out and touch.

320
00:31:29,628 --> 00:31:31,171
She would have said yes.

321
00:31:31,254 --> 00:31:33,006
Well, try again later.

322
00:31:33,131 --> 00:31:34,883
Try what later?

323
00:31:34,966 --> 00:31:36,635
I just heard
from the people in Sirmione.

324
00:31:36,718 --> 00:31:38,553
They say they've come up with something.

325
00:31:38,637 --> 00:31:40,931
Fantastic.

326
00:31:41,014 --> 00:31:42,557
Going there today.

327
00:31:42,641 --> 00:31:45,041
Would you like to come along?
I would love to. Thank you.

328
00:31:46,520 --> 00:31:48,563
Smell this.
Can I come, too?

329
00:31:48,647 --> 00:31:51,233
On the condition you remain silent.

330
00:31:51,858 --> 00:31:53,211
Silent as in,
"He has too many opinions,"

331
00:31:53,235 --> 00:31:54,875
or silent as in,
"Just not telling anybody

332
00:31:54,903 --> 00:31:56,571
"what an amazing thing you've dug up"?

333
00:31:56,655 --> 00:31:58,198
Well, nothing has been dug up.

334
00:31:58,281 --> 00:32:00,909
It's what has been brought out,
out of the water.

335
00:32:09,668 --> 00:32:11,127
What are you doing?

336
00:32:11,253 --> 00:32:13,171
Going to Lake Garda with my dad.

337
00:32:13,255 --> 00:32:15,257
He wants to show Oliver
where he's dredging.

338
00:32:16,216 --> 00:32:17,592
Can you tell him I came by?

339
00:32:18,552 --> 00:32:20,428
He's inside with my dad, helping him.

340
00:32:22,264 --> 00:32:25,684
You were amazing last night,
on the dance floor.

341
00:32:25,767 --> 00:32:27,644
He's a good dancer.
A good dancer.

342
00:32:30,021 --> 00:32:31,690
He's good-looking too.

343
00:32:33,149 --> 00:32:34,943
Want to get us together?
No.

344
00:32:36,695 --> 00:32:38,363
Come in.

345
00:33:15,108 --> 00:33:17,652
Dad always sits up front
with Anchise to navigate.

346
00:33:25,243 --> 00:33:27,704
She seems to like you a lot.

347
00:33:27,787 --> 00:33:30,457
She's more beautiful
than she was last year.

348
00:33:31,875 --> 00:33:35,337
I saw her naked on a night swim once.

349
00:33:35,420 --> 00:33:37,380
Great body.

350
00:33:37,547 --> 00:33:39,132
Trying to get me to like her?

351
00:33:39,257 --> 00:33:41,301
What would be the harm in that?

352
00:33:41,426 --> 00:33:42,594
No, no harm.

353
00:33:42,677 --> 00:33:45,477
Just typically like to go at those
things on my own, if you don't mind.

354
00:33:49,643 --> 00:33:50,894
I'll drive today!

355
00:33:55,273 --> 00:33:57,275
Just don't play at being the good host.

356
00:33:59,152 --> 00:34:02,572
Anchise, take the afternoon off.

357
00:34:04,866 --> 00:34:06,409
What's going on, boys?

358
00:34:07,661 --> 00:34:13,041
Oliver, come. Sit up front.
Be my navigator.

359
00:34:13,124 --> 00:34:15,585
What? What?

360
00:34:30,642 --> 00:34:32,811
Dr. Roseburg.
Samuel!

361
00:34:32,894 --> 00:34:34,854
Benvenuto.
Look who's here.

362
00:34:36,439 --> 00:34:38,199
He's grown a bit, eh?
And this is Oliver.

363
00:35:07,721 --> 00:35:09,472
Sammy! Come on!

364
00:35:22,527 --> 00:35:23,987
Truce?

365
00:35:25,613 --> 00:35:27,282
Hey, boys.

366
00:35:32,996 --> 00:35:38,251
The ship went down in 1827
on the way to Isola del Garda.

367
00:35:38,334 --> 00:35:42,464
Gossip has it this statue
was a gift from Count Lechi

368
00:35:42,547 --> 00:35:45,717
to his lover,
contralto Adelaide Malanotte.

369
00:35:48,136 --> 00:35:52,515
There are four known sets,
after the Praxiteles originals.

370
00:35:52,599 --> 00:35:54,142
This fellow's at number three.

371
00:35:54,225 --> 00:35:56,811
The Emperor Hadrian had a pair,
dug up at Tivoli,

372
00:35:56,895 --> 00:36:00,815
but one of the more philistine
of the Farnese Popes melted them down

373
00:36:00,899 --> 00:36:04,736
and had them recast as a
particularly voluptuous Venus.

374
00:36:25,298 --> 00:36:28,635
Who'd like to go for a swim
before we head back?

375
00:36:28,718 --> 00:36:34,015
We're all such pros. If I got my own
statue, it would probably be on there.

376
00:36:40,897 --> 00:36:42,524
Elio!

377
00:36:42,607 --> 00:36:44,567
Oliver!

378
00:36:47,987 --> 00:36:49,906
I have to go. I have to go.
Hey! Hey!

379
00:36:49,989 --> 00:36:51,699
I have to go.

380
00:36:53,493 --> 00:36:55,036
Goodness.

381
00:36:58,832 --> 00:37:01,125
Are you going, too?
No, no.

382
00:37:01,209 --> 00:37:03,294
I should stay
and do some work on my book.

383
00:37:03,378 --> 00:37:05,964
Come on. How about a drink
to celebrate the day?

384
00:37:06,756 --> 00:37:09,259
Okay, maybe just one.
All right!

385
00:37:20,520 --> 00:37:21,980
Marzia?

386
00:38:26,628 --> 00:38:29,589
The Cosmic Fragments by Heraclitus.

387
00:38:37,805 --> 00:38:41,059
The meaning of the river flowing
is not that all things are changing

388
00:38:41,142 --> 00:38:43,144
so that we cannot encounter them twice,

389
00:38:43,227 --> 00:38:46,356
but that some things
stay the same only by changing.

390
00:39:34,237 --> 00:39:36,990
Sorry, Elio.
I brought some clean clothes.

391
00:39:42,078 --> 00:39:43,538
Leave the door open.

392
00:39:44,664 --> 00:39:46,332
Thanks.
You're welcome.

393
00:42:35,126 --> 00:42:37,044
Darling, have you seen my Heptaméron?

394
00:42:40,173 --> 00:42:41,299
Mafalda.

395
00:42:46,137 --> 00:42:47,597
It's in German.

396
00:42:49,807 --> 00:42:50,850
Okay.

397
00:42:53,603 --> 00:42:57,398
I can't remember where we left off,
but I think you'll like this one.

398
00:43:00,651 --> 00:43:02,570
Come here, darling.

399
00:43:04,530 --> 00:43:06,324
So, I'll translate, huh?

400
00:43:15,583 --> 00:43:19,754
"A handsome young knight
is madly in love with a princess.

401
00:43:19,921 --> 00:43:21,839
"And she, too, is in love with him,

402
00:43:23,174 --> 00:43:26,552
"though she seems not to be
entirely aware of it.

403
00:43:27,595 --> 00:43:29,347
"Despite the friendship..."

404
00:43:31,807 --> 00:43:34,936
"...that blossoms between them,

405
00:43:35,978 --> 00:43:38,856
"or perhaps because of
that very friendship,

406
00:43:40,066 --> 00:43:42,443
"the young knight finds himself so..."

407
00:43:45,655 --> 00:43:47,949
"...so humbled and speechless

408
00:43:48,908 --> 00:43:53,037
"that he's totally unable to bring up
the subject of his love.

409
00:43:53,913 --> 00:43:57,625
"Till one day, he asks the princess
point-blank..."

410
00:44:08,970 --> 00:44:11,138
"Is it better to speak or to die?"

411
00:44:16,519 --> 00:44:19,563
I'd never have the courage
to ask a question like that.

412
00:44:21,148 --> 00:44:22,400
I doubt that.

413
00:44:27,154 --> 00:44:29,532
Hey, Elly-Belly.

414
00:44:31,325 --> 00:44:33,494
You do know that
you can always talk to us.

415
00:44:40,167 --> 00:44:43,254
My mom's been reading
this 16th-century French romance.

416
00:44:43,379 --> 00:44:45,899
She read some of it to my dad and I
the day the lights went out.

417
00:44:46,507 --> 00:44:49,093
Yeah, about the knight that doesn't know
whether to speak or die?

418
00:44:49,176 --> 00:44:50,261
Right.

419
00:44:51,512 --> 00:44:52,930
So, does he or doesn't he?

420
00:44:54,932 --> 00:44:56,726
"Better to speak," she said.

421
00:44:58,686 --> 00:45:00,438
But she's on her guard.

422
00:45:01,814 --> 00:45:03,733
She senses a trap somewhere.

423
00:45:10,698 --> 00:45:11,991
So, does he speak?

424
00:45:13,242 --> 00:45:14,327
No.

425
00:45:16,620 --> 00:45:17,747
He fudges.

426
00:45:19,832 --> 00:45:22,209
It figures. He's French.

427
00:45:28,466 --> 00:45:30,843
I gotta go to town in a little bit
to pick some things up.

428
00:45:30,926 --> 00:45:34,388
I can go. I'm not doing anything today.

429
00:45:35,681 --> 00:45:37,141
Then why don't we go together?

430
00:45:37,224 --> 00:45:38,392
Right now?

431
00:45:38,476 --> 00:45:40,686
Yeah. Right now.

432
00:45:41,729 --> 00:45:44,207
That is, of course, unless you have
more important business going on.

433
00:45:44,231 --> 00:45:47,031
"That is, of course, unless you have
more important business going on."

434
00:45:58,913 --> 00:45:59,973
Mind if I put this in your bag?

435
00:45:59,997 --> 00:46:00,998
Yes, please.

436
00:46:12,093 --> 00:46:14,095
I straightened the wheels
and inflated the tires.

437
00:46:14,178 --> 00:46:15,596
Perfect. Thanks.

438
00:46:17,765 --> 00:46:22,144
I fell. I was coming home the other day,
and I scraped myself pretty badly.

439
00:46:22,436 --> 00:46:25,022
Anchise insisted on applying
some sort of witches' brew.

440
00:46:25,231 --> 00:46:26,649
I think it helped.

441
00:46:51,006 --> 00:46:52,383
Hold this for a second, will you?

442
00:47:12,278 --> 00:47:13,612
Want one?
Sure.

443
00:47:38,471 --> 00:47:39,555
Not bad, huh?

444
00:47:40,347 --> 00:47:41,474
Not bad at all.

445
00:47:44,518 --> 00:47:45,811
I thought you didn't smoke.

446
00:47:47,438 --> 00:47:48,522
I don't.

447
00:47:54,153 --> 00:47:57,156
So, World War II, huh?
No. This is World War I.

448
00:47:57,948 --> 00:48:00,508
You'd have to be at least 80 years old
to have known any of them.

449
00:48:01,535 --> 00:48:03,621
I never even heard
of the Battle of Piave.

450
00:48:03,746 --> 00:48:06,373
Battle of Piave was one of the most
lethal battles of World War I.

451
00:48:07,041 --> 00:48:08,751
Hundred and seventy thousand
people died.

452
00:48:10,294 --> 00:48:12,129
Is there anything you don't know?

453
00:48:16,091 --> 00:48:17,551
I know nothing, Oliver.

454
00:48:22,640 --> 00:48:24,367
Well, you seem to know
more than anybody else around here.

455
00:48:24,391 --> 00:48:27,152
Well, if you only knew how little
I know about the things that matter.

456
00:48:30,064 --> 00:48:31,440
What things that matter?

457
00:48:38,781 --> 00:48:39,907
You know what things.

458
00:48:47,122 --> 00:48:48,457
Why are you telling me this?

459
00:48:52,920 --> 00:48:54,240
'Cause I thought you should know.

460
00:48:56,048 --> 00:48:57,841
Because you thought I should know?

461
00:49:00,636 --> 00:49:01,971
'Cause I wanted you to know?

462
00:49:05,558 --> 00:49:07,518
Because I wanted you to know.

463
00:49:11,564 --> 00:49:13,232
Because I wanted you to know.

464
00:49:18,112 --> 00:49:20,447
'Cause I wanted you to know.

465
00:49:31,375 --> 00:49:34,211
Because there's no one else
I can say this to but you.

466
00:49:40,968 --> 00:49:42,720
Are you saying
what I think you're saying?

467
00:49:50,102 --> 00:49:52,396
Don't go anywhere. Stay right here.

468
00:49:53,814 --> 00:49:55,482
You know I'm not going anywhere.

469
00:50:24,928 --> 00:50:26,472
They mixed up all of my pages.

470
00:50:26,555 --> 00:50:28,682
I'm gonna have to
retype this whole thing.

471
00:50:29,183 --> 00:50:30,619
I'm not gonna have anything to work on
this afternoon.

472
00:50:30,643 --> 00:50:32,186
This is gonna set me back a whole day.

473
00:50:33,020 --> 00:50:34,063
Damn it.

474
00:50:35,356 --> 00:50:37,274
Shouldn't have said anything.

475
00:50:37,566 --> 00:50:38,734
Just pretend you never did.

476
00:50:38,817 --> 00:50:41,070
Does that mean we're on speaking terms
but not really?

477
00:50:44,573 --> 00:50:46,909
It means we can't talk
about those kinds of things.

478
00:50:48,035 --> 00:50:49,286
Okay?

479
00:50:51,038 --> 00:50:52,247
We just can't.

480
00:51:07,346 --> 00:51:08,555
Hey.

481
00:51:09,431 --> 00:51:11,308
Let's go, American!

482
00:51:32,287 --> 00:51:34,039
Ready?
Let's go.

483
00:52:09,700 --> 00:52:10,826
Pretty much.

484
00:52:19,126 --> 00:52:20,627
Oh, my God.

485
00:52:21,086 --> 00:52:22,755
Thirsty?
Yeah.

486
00:52:25,048 --> 00:52:26,633
Good morning, ma'am.

487
00:52:28,218 --> 00:52:29,511
Excuse me.

488
00:52:30,429 --> 00:52:33,140
Could I ask for a glass of water?

489
00:52:43,859 --> 00:52:45,152
I'll Duce.

490
00:52:45,235 --> 00:52:47,029
"People of Italy!"

491
00:52:48,280 --> 00:52:49,531
That's Italy.

492
00:52:53,494 --> 00:52:55,037
Thank you.
You're welcome.

493
00:53:33,867 --> 00:53:34,868
Come on!

494
00:53:56,890 --> 00:53:59,309
This is my spot. It's all mine.

495
00:54:01,311 --> 00:54:02,646
Come here to read.

496
00:54:04,106 --> 00:54:06,066
Can't tell you the number of books
I've read here.

497
00:54:08,777 --> 00:54:11,154
Oh, my God, it's freezing.

498
00:54:12,114 --> 00:54:13,740
Spring is in the mountains.

499
00:54:14,575 --> 00:54:15,993
The Alpi Orobie.

500
00:54:17,327 --> 00:54:18,927
The water comes
straight down from there.

501
00:54:45,022 --> 00:54:46,899
I like the way you say things.

502
00:54:46,982 --> 00:54:49,382
I don't know why you're always
putting yourself down, though.

503
00:54:49,610 --> 00:54:51,612
So you won't, I guess.

504
00:54:55,949 --> 00:54:57,951
You really that afraid of what I think?

505
00:55:10,881 --> 00:55:12,561
You're making things
very difficult for me.

506
00:55:25,562 --> 00:55:27,105
I love this, Oliver.

507
00:55:32,986 --> 00:55:33,987
What?

508
00:55:38,325 --> 00:55:39,451
Everything.

509
00:55:44,498 --> 00:55:45,874
Us, you mean?

510
00:55:47,751 --> 00:55:49,002
It's not bad.

511
00:55:50,087 --> 00:55:51,129
It's not bad.

512
00:56:46,101 --> 00:56:47,185
Better now?

513
00:56:55,777 --> 00:56:57,821
No, no, no.

514
00:56:58,905 --> 00:57:00,532
We should go.
Why?

515
00:57:01,074 --> 00:57:03,910
I know myself. Okay?
And we've been good.

516
00:57:03,994 --> 00:57:05,304
We haven't done anything
to be ashamed of,

517
00:57:05,328 --> 00:57:06,621
and that's a good thing.

518
00:57:07,247 --> 00:57:08,415
I wanna be good.

519
00:57:09,166 --> 00:57:10,167
Okay?

520
00:57:17,090 --> 00:57:18,800
Am I offending you?

521
00:57:25,682 --> 00:57:26,850
Just don't.

522
00:57:33,982 --> 00:57:36,151
I think it's starting to get infected.

523
00:57:38,111 --> 00:57:39,991
We can stop by the pharmacist's
on the way back.

524
00:57:40,363 --> 00:57:41,782
Excellent idea.

525
00:57:48,830 --> 00:57:52,334
So we got the government
of Bettino Craxi...

526
00:57:52,459 --> 00:57:54,961
Because we don't do anything
but talk, talk, talk.

527
00:57:55,087 --> 00:57:56,963
Let me speak.

528
00:57:57,089 --> 00:58:00,592
We have five parties
